item.title: AII-AIMEP-2501: Provision of the Australia-Indonesia Muslim Exchange Program (AIMEP)
item.description: DFAT is seeking a service provider to design and deliver the annual Australia-Indonesia Muslim Exchange Program (AIMEP) for two years from April 2026 to March 2028. AIMEP is one of the Australian-Indonesia Institute’s (AII) longstanding, annual flagship exchange programs. Established in 2002, AIMEP is an intensive program of intercultural and interreligious exchange that brings together Muslim changemakers, community activists and emerging leaders from across Indonesia and Australia, often with ministerial engagement. Delegates undertake immersion programs in Australia and Indonesia where they experience the other's culture and society and engage with leading academics, religious and community leaders, and government representatives.

item.title: AII-AIYEP-2502: Provision of the Australia-Indonesia Youth Exchange Program (AIYEP)
item.description: DFAT is seeking a service provider to design and deliver the annual Australia-Indonesia Youth Exchange Program (AIYEP) for two years from April 2026 to March 2028. AIYEP is one of the Australian-Indonesia Institute’s (AII) longstanding, annual flagship exchange programs. Established in 1982, AIYEP links Australian and Indonesian youth (aged 21-25) through social, professional, and cultural exchange. Delivered in partnership with Kemenpora, the Indonesian Ministry of Youth and Sport, AIYEP aims to foster mutual understanding and increase cultural literacy and capability. Program delegates grow their intercultural skills and international networks through internships, language training, academic workshops and cultural activities, including undertaking immersion programs in each country.

item.title: PROC-9177310: Measuring profitability and productivity impacts of improved farm safety
item.description: One consistent barrier to farm safety implementation identified is a “myth” that “it costs money to be safe” and these changes would negatively impact on farm profitability and productivity.  This investment proposes to examine the impact of improved farm safety practices on farm business profitability and productivity via an analysis of growers of varying scale who have implemented farm safety practices.  This analysis will quantify the actual impact and test whether these changes negatively impact on farm profitability and productivity.

This EOI process provides an opportunity for interested entities to demonstrate their skills, capabilities and capacity to contribute to the final Detailed Design through completion of the Requirements as set out in the EOI documentation.

The EOI is Stage One of a potential two-stage Process.

Participation in this EOI process does not automatically entitle a Respondent to participate in any subsequent process and no contractual obligations will result from this EOI.

item.title: PROC-9177370: NGN Identifying, understanding and meeting the yield potential of Faba beans in Northern NSW
item.description: This investment will research the key factors affecting the yield of Faba beans in Northern NSW. Faba beans are an important rotation crop and provide residual benefits to soil health, however it is common to witness considerable yield variations within fields and on farms. These limitations can severely impact the gross margins of local growers. This project will assess optimal yields across different locations and examine the factors linked to reduced production. By identifying these constraints, growers can implement strategies to mitigate their impact. The study will contain experiments conducted over three years based in Northern NSW.
